thread.title: 'It's a central banker's world,' strategist says
thread.title_full: 'It's a central banker's world,' strategist says

author: Fred Imbert
title: 'It's a central banker's world,' strategist says
text:
Fed impact into 2016
Russell Investments market strategist Steve Wood, says he expects the Fed to leverage a "deflationary mindset."
Central bank policy will be the primary catalyst for financial markets, Russell Investments's Steven Wood said Monday.
"Mario Draghi last week reminded us how much of a central banker's world it was, so that liquidity has been well received," the firm's chief market strategist told CNBC's " Squawk on the Street ."
On Thursday, the European Central Bank president left the door open for more quantitative easing after the bank kept interest rates low. The ECB began its QE program on March.
On Friday, the People's Bank of China cut its benchmark interest rates for the sixth time since November.
Both central bank moves helped U.S. stocks rally last week, as all major indexes gained more than 2 percent despite mixed earnings.
‹ Why Fed wants to keep us guessing: Ex-Fed official The Fed's next move? Negative interest rates › "The third quarter is going to be very tough on the earnings front, but fourth quarter could stabilize a bit, and as we push into 2016, we'll begin to see some of the positives from the oil-price drop over the last year," Wood said.
This week, investors will keep an eye on the Federal Reserve's two-day policy meeting, which ends Wednesday.
"We think that the Fed is probably going to do nothing this week. The December meeting for a rate hike I still think is a live meeting," Wood said.
The Fed kept interest rates at near-zero percent at its last meeting, citing a number of factors including global growth concerns.
"Globally, things have not looked good for a while. If you look around, Latin America has been problematic and Europe's been that way for a while. I think what you're seeing here is a continuation of this rather sluggish 2.1 percent [growth]," John Taylor, senior fellow in economics at the Hoover Institution, said in another " Squawk on the Street " interview.
